280-283. metu, “from fear;'’ i.e. in consequence of her fear for Carthage. Compare id metuens, &c., 111 ν. 23 above—consilia in melias reseret, “shall alter [or mend] her plans for the better.” in melite-s = εἷς τὸ βέλτιον. The word referet implies a. previous digression on the part of Juno from the proper course—tomiano. The toga was the distinguishing dress of a Roman citizen. When, therefore, Virgil speaks of his counirymen as rerum dominos, he pays tribute to their prowess in war, whilst the expression yentem toyatam contains, an allusion to their pre-eminence in the arts of peace.
